  Abstract                 = {This chapter describes prostanoids and explains the cyclooxygenase, lipoxygenase, and epoxygenase pathways. Prostanoids, which include the prostaglandins and thromboxanes are formed by the action of cyclooxygenases and have their aliphatic side chains emanating from C-8 and C-12 of the cyclopentane ring. Leukotrienes are produced by the action of 5-1ipoxygenase (5-LO), and the biosynthesis of leukotrienes within cells is highly regulated and depends not only on the availability of arachidonic acid and molecular oxygen, but also on the subcellular location of 5-LO. The conversion of leukotrienes into alternative structural entities is an important feature of inactivation of these potent biologically active eicosanoids. Numerous lipoxygenases occur within the plant and animal kingdoms; however, the overall biological activities of the lipoxygenase products are not completely known. The currently known biological actions of leukotrienes all involve cell membrane G-protein-linked receptors, yet an understanding of why biosynthesis of these lipophilic molecules occurs deep within the cell remains a mystery. Thus, considerable challenges remain in understanding the detailed biochemistry involved in the synthesis and release of biologically active leukotrienes.},
